all the work for you.

71
00:02:56,970 --> 00:02:59,040
You don't have to manage it.

72
00:02:59,040 --> 00:03:01,020
You don't have to tell it what to do.

73
00:03:01,020 --> 00:03:04,950
Number two, it continually
scans your resources.

74
00:03:04,950 --> 00:03:07,140
So in that dynamic cloud environment,

75
00:03:07,140 --> 00:03:09,750
as resources come up,

76
00:03:09,750 --> 00:03:11,580
Inspector sees them, it scans them,

77
00:03:11,580 --> 00:03:15,187
and as resources goes
down, Amazon sees that

78
00:03:15,187 --> 00:03:17,937
and will automatically
close findings for you.

79
00:03:17,937 --> 00:03:20,610
You don't have to manage
the service for you,

80
00:03:20,610 --> 00:03:21,750
it does it.

81
00:03:21,750 --> 00:03:24,493
Our goal is for you to
worry about remediation

82
00:03:24,493 --> 00:03:26,490
and taking action,

83
00:03:26,490 --> 00:03:27,870
and that's it.

84
00:03:27,870 --> 00:03:30,180
So when we launched Amazon Inspector,

85
00:03:30,180 --> 00:03:31,560
we launched it with support

86
00:03:31,560 --> 00:03:35,460
for virtual machines through Amazon EC2,

87
00:03:35,460 --> 00:03:38,730
container images through Amazon ECR,

88
00:03:38,730 --> 00:03:42,270
and then we added support
for serverless functions

89
00:03:42,270 --> 00:03:44,010
through AWS Lambda.

90
00:03:44,010 --> 00:03:45,780
And then most recently this year,

91
00:03:45,780 --> 00:03:49,260
we also support manage code repositories

92
00:03:49,260 --> 00:03:50,610
through our interactions

93
00:03:50,610 --> 00:03:53,073
and interfaces to GitHub and GitLab.

94
00:03:55,620 --> 00:04:00,360
So really a quick overview
of Amazon Inspector.

95
00:04:00,360 --> 00:04:02,700
When we talk about Amazon Inspector

96
00:04:02,700 --> 00:04:04,320
and how you use it,

97
00:04:04,320 --> 00:04:07,560
we really talk about
four different phases.

98
00:04:07,560 --> 00:04:09,450
Phase one is enablement.

99
00:04:09,450 --> 00:04:11,010
And this is, as a customer,

100
00:04:11,010 --> 00:04:13,923
you going in and turning
Amazon Inspector on

101
00:04:13,923 --> 00:04:16,470
either for your account

102
00:04:16,470 --> 00:04:19,080
or for your entire organization.

103
00:04:19,080 --> 00:04:20,520
You can do both.

104
00:04:20,520 --> 00:04:22,620
Second, once you do that,

105
00:04:22,620 --> 00:04:26,820
Amazon Inspector will start
looking at your environment.

106
00:04:26,820 --> 00:04:29,340
It will discover all your resources

107
00:04:29,340 --> 00:04:31,110
and scan those resources

108
00:04:31,110 --> 00:04:35,340
to get a initial set of findings

109
00:04:35,340 --> 00:04:37,320
so that you know where you are from

110
00:04:37,320 --> 00:04:39,090
in terms of your exposures

111
00:04:39,090 --> 00:04:41,700
and then it'll start monitoring.

112
00:04:41,700 --> 00:04:44,640
So as changes take place,

113
00:04:44,640 --> 00:04:47,700
Amazon Inspector follows suit.

114
00:04:47,700 --> 00:04:50,700
Third phase is looking at your findings.

115
00:04:50,700 --> 00:04:53,820
Inspector will contextualize your findings

116
00:04:53,820 --> 00:04:57,300
so that you can prioritize
what's important.

117
00:04:57,300 --> 00:04:59,463
Severity is not the only critical thing.

118
00:04:59,463 --> 00:05:02,370
Some of your resources are exposed

119
00:05:02,370 --> 00:05:04,410
to the internet, some of them are not.

120
00:05:04,410 --> 00:05:06,360
Some of them have vulnerabilities

121
00:05:06,360 --> 00:05:07,440
that can be exploited,

122
00:05:07,440 --> 00:05:08,610
some of them don't.

123
00:05:08,610 --> 00:05:11,760
Inspector takes a lot of different pieces

124
00:05:11,760 --> 00:05:15,270
of information together to
give you a prioritization score

125
00:05:15,270 --> 00:05:17,430
that you can use to take action.

126
00:05:17,430 --> 00:05:20,550
And taking action is our fourth phase

127
00:05:20,550 --> 00:05:22,500
where once you have your findings,

128
00:05:22,500 --> 00:05:24,240
where do you want to do your work?

129
00:05:24,240 --> 00:05:26,040
You can do your work in Inspector,

130
00:05:26,040 --> 00:05:27,330
you can do it in Security Hub.

131
00:05:27,330 --> 00:05:30,060
We give you lots of different options.

132
00:05:30,060 --> 00:05:32,913
We're gonna dig into each
one of these quickly.

133
00:05:34,890 --> 00:05:37,368
So number one, like I said,

134
00:05:37,368 --> 00:05:39,930
when you turn on Amazon Inspector,

135
00:05:39,930 --> 00:05:42,300
you can enable it for your account

136
00:05:42,300 --> 00:05:46,350
or you can enable it for
your entire organization.

137
00:05:46,350 --> 00:05:49,830
We see most of our customers
turning on Inspector

138
00:05:49,830 --> 00:05:52,620
for their entire organization.

139
00:05:52,620 --> 00:05:55,410
What they do is they use
their management account

140
00:05:55,410 --> 00:05:58,860
to assign a delegated administrator.

141
00:05:58,860 --> 00:06:01,620
And from that delegated
administrator account,

142
00:06:01,620 --> 00:06:06,060
they can tell Amazon
Inspector what to scan

143
00:06:06,060 --> 00:06:07,770
and based on what settings.

144
00:06:07,770 --> 00:06:09,660
And we also provide you a way

145
00:06:09,660 --> 00:06:12,420
of automatically enabling Inspector

146
00:06:12,420 --> 00:06:16,410
for all new accounts added
to your organization.

147
00:06:16,410 --> 00:06:19,260
And the power of that is
once you get it set up,

148
00:06:19,260 --> 00:06:22,320
if you say turn it on
for all new accounts,

149
00:06:22,320 --> 00:06:25,470
you no longer have to worry
about having gaps in coverage.

150
00:06:25,470 --> 00:06:29,070
Inspector will enable
itself automatically.

151
00:06:29,070 --> 00:06:33,150
Secondly, that delegated
administrator account,

152
00:06:33,150 --> 00:06:37,200
not only does it configure
your entire organization,

153
00:06:37,200 --> 00:06:41,250
it also has visibility into
your entire organization.

154
00:06:41,250 --> 00:06:44,269
So as a user within the
delegated administrator account,

155
00:06:44,269 --> 00:06:46,890
you have a centralized view

156
00:06:46,890 --> 00:06:49,770
of all your findings
regardless of the account.

157
00:06:49,770 --> 00:06:50,970
As a customer,

158
00:06:50,970 --> 00:06:54,090
you can manage all your
findings for your organization

159
00:06:54,090 --> 00:06:57,330
from that one view while
your individual accounts

160
00:06:57,330 --> 00:07:01,320
still have visibility
into their own findings.

161
00:07:01,320 --> 00:07:04,800
So if you cut a ticket to
one of your teams saying,

162
00:07:04,800 --> 00:07:06,750
hey, you have this vulnerability,

163
00:07:06,750 --> 00:07:07,890
they can go in Inspector,

164
00:07:07,890 --> 00:07:10,200
they'll see the exact same details

165
00:07:10,200 --> 00:07:12,828
that the delegated administrator sees.

166
00:07:12,828 --> 00:07:15,143
We launched with this capability

167
00:07:15,143 --> 00:07:18,000
when Inspector launched
a couple years ago,

168
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:20,670
and we also upgraded that capability

169
00:07:20,670 --> 00:07:25,670
to do an organization
configuration enablement

170
00:07:25,830 --> 00:07:29,280
through support for organization policies

171
00:07:29,280 --> 00:07:30,730
that just launched this year.

172
00:07:32,580 --> 00:07:37,580
Phase two is the discover,
scan and monitor phase.

173
00:07:37,770 --> 00:07:42,300
And this is where Amazon
Inspector, when you turn it on,

174
00:07:42,300 --> 00:07:45,120
it sees all of your resources.

175
00:07:45,120 --> 00:07:49,110
So if you ever want to know
what are your accounts running,

176
00:07:49,110 --> 00:07:51,360
what are the resources,
what do they look like,

177
00:07:51,360 --> 00:07:53,130
Amazon Inspector knows.

178
00:07:53,130 --> 00:07:55,710
It sees these resources as they launch,

179
00:07:55,710 --> 00:07:58,511
it sees these resources as they terminate

180
00:07:58,511 --> 00:08:00,960
and it updates accordingly.

181
00:08:00,960 --> 00:08:04,800
Like I said before, we
support EC2 instances,

182
00:08:04,800 --> 00:08:08,760
container images and ECR, Lambda functions

183
00:08:08,760 --> 00:08:11,760
and now manage code repositories.

184
00:08:11,760 --> 00:08:14,790
Inspector works in near real time.

185
00:08:14,790 --> 00:08:16,620
So that as changes occur,

186
00:08:16,620 --> 00:08:19,653
you get those findings right away.

187
00:08:20,580 --> 00:08:23,610
Amazon Inspector is also intelligent.

188
00:08:23,610 --> 00:08:25,710
We talked about one of the challenges

189
00:08:25,710 --> 00:08:28,320
of traditional vulnerability management

190
00:08:28,320 --> 00:08:31,020
where you, as a customer, have to decide

191
00:08:31,020 --> 00:08:32,760
when you're going to scan.

192
00:08:32,760 --> 00:08:34,830
You don't know if you're
catching everything.

193
00:08:34,830 --> 00:08:38,670
Here, Inspector monitors your environment

194
00:08:38,670 --> 00:08:41,070
and scans when it needs to scan.

195
00:08:41,070 --> 00:08:43,200
If a new resource is launched,

196
00:08:43,200 --> 00:08:45,270
Amazon Inspector scans it.

197
00:08:45,270 --> 00:08:48,780
If you install a new software
package on a resource,

198
00:08:48,780 --> 00:08:50,820
Amazon Inspector scans it.

199
00:08:50,820 --> 00:08:54,810
If you patch, Amazon Inspector
sees that patch, rescans

200
00:08:54,810 --> 00:08:58,800
and the findings for
vulnerability are now remediated,

201
00:08:58,800 --> 00:09:00,750
it will close those findings.

202
00:09:00,750 --> 00:09:04,571
If there's a new CVE published,
Amazon Inspector knows

203
00:09:04,571 --> 00:09:07,140
which of your resources have that package

204
00:09:07,140 --> 00:09:08,407
and will automatically re-scan.

205
00:09:08,407 --> 00:09:11,170
So that at any point in time,

206
00:09:11,170 --> 00:09:14,250
you can go to Amazon Inspector know

207
00:09:14,250 --> 00:09:17,550
what is your security posture
at that moment in time.

208
00:09:17,550 --> 00:09:19,700
You don't have to do
any work to get there.

209
00:09:20,880 --> 00:09:24,180
And then phase three is contextualization

210
00:09:24,180 --> 00:09:25,830
of those findings.

211
00:09:25,830 --> 00:09:27,540
Amazon Inspector supports

212
00:09:27,540 --> 00:09:30,720
what we call the Amazon Inspector Score,

213
00:09:30,720 --> 00:09:32,010
and this tries to answer

214
00:09:32,010 --> 00:09:34,710
a whole bunch of questions that you have.

215
00:09:34,710 --> 00:09:38,340
One question may be: what is
the most severe vulnerability

216
00:09:38,340 --> 00:09:40,980
that I need to remediate?

217
00:09:40,980 --> 00:09:44,580
Is it for a resource that's exposed?

218
00:09:44,580 --> 00:09:48,000
Does that vulnerability have a exploit?

219
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:50,460
Is that exploit common in a wild?

220
00:09:50,460 --> 00:09:52,830
Amazon uses all that information

221
00:09:52,830 --> 00:09:57,180
in order to score up or score
down your vulnerabilities.

222
00:09:57,180 --> 00:10:00,150
So that when you look at
Amazon Inspector's score,

223
00:10:00,150 --> 00:10:02,670
you're truly looking at
the most important things

224
00:10:02,670 --> 00:10:05,283
for you to fix within your environment.

225
00:10:06,960 --> 00:10:10,560
We do this using a bunch of advanced

226
00:10:10,560 --> 00:10:13,260
vulnerability intelligence information

227
00:10:13,260 --> 00:10:17,370
that we partner with
Recorded Future to gather.

228
00:10:17,370 --> 00:10:20,340
So as a security professional,

229
00:10:20,340 --> 00:10:22,470
you can go in and see,

230
00:10:22,470 --> 00:10:24,113
okay, this vulnerability,

231
00:10:24,113 --> 00:10:27,840
how is it mapped to MITRE ATT&CK TTPs?

232
00:10:27,840 --> 00:10:31,040
Is there a known CISA exploit?

233
00:10:31,040 --> 00:10:32,820
Is it there a malware kit for it?

234
00:10:32,820 --> 00:10:36,030
Is this commonly exploited in the wild

235
00:10:36,030 --> 00:10:37,860
so that you can double check our work

236
00:10:37,860 --> 00:10:39,450
and make your own decisions as well

237
00:10:39,450 --> 00:10:41,703
as to what you wanna remediate first?

